<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1105,2020]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Frustules rectangular in girdle view. Valves lanceolate in larger specimens to rhombic-lanceolate in smaller specimens. Valve ends broadly protracted and broadly rounded. In shorter size diminution stages the protraction of valve ends not as clearly pronounced as in longer valves. Valve length 
<quantity box="[1183,1355,1182,1208]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="2.25" metricValueMin="1.05" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="22.5" valueMin="10.5">10.5–22.5 µm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[151,295,1221,1247]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="3.9" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="4.4" valueMax="4.9" valueMin="3.9">3.9–4.9 µm</quantity>
. Axial area very narrow-linear, rarely observed as weakly broadened close to the mid-valve. Central area variable, transversally elongated to panduriform, defined by shortening of a single central stria from both valve sides. In some specimens, central area forming well-defined fascia, continuously broadening towards the margins. Terminal area clearly distinguishable throughout size diminution stages, quite broad, semi-elliptical in shape. Raphe linear-filiform, with teardrop-shaped, closely spaced central pores. Terminal pores of raphe distinguishable in LM view, equally pronounced as central pores. Striae coarse, moderately to strongly radiate in middle, becoming parallel or weakly convergent towards valve ends. Striae continuing on valve mantle with the same pattern as on valve face (
<figureCitation box="[779,947,1492,1518]" captionStart="FIGURES 308–364" captionStartId="47.[151,269,1730,1754]" captionTargetBox="[289,1301,194,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-72@47.[264,1323,194,1706]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 308–364: LM micrographs. Figs 308–328. Hippodonta avittatiformis (type material). Figs 327, 328. Images of complete frustules in girdle view. Figs 329–342. Hippodonta angustata (type material). Figs 343–349. Hippodonta cocquytiae (type material). Figs 350–353. Hippodonta conspicua (type material). Figs 354–364. Hippodonta minuta (type material). Fig. 354. Complete frustule in girdle view. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5072000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5072000/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs 327, 328</figureCitation>
). Striae evenly spaced throughout, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" metricValueMax="3.556" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="in" value="12.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="10.0">10–14 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[183,265,1530,1556]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. Interstriae of equal or greater width than the striae. Lineolae composing the striae quite densely spaced within a stria, not distinguishable in LM view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1105,2020]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1607,1633]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Distribution</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[388,698,1608,1633]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittatiformis">
<emphasis box="[388,698,1608,1633]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Hippodonta avittatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has so far only been observed from Lake Tanganyika, East Africa. In the 
<typeStatus box="[315,365,1646,1672]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
material it is very frequent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1105,2020]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,364,1685,1711]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Observations</emphasis>
:—With regard to the striae morphology and pattern and the valve outline, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[1242,1436,1685,1710]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittatiformis">
<emphasis box="[1242,1436,1685,1710]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H. avittatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cholnoky) Lange-Bert., Metzeltin &amp; Witkowski" authorityName="Lange-Bert., Metzeltin &amp; Witkowski" baseAuthorityName="Cholnoky" box="[280,1012,1724,1750]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittata">
<emphasis box="[280,301,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[317,409,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittata</emphasis>
(Cholnoky) Lange-Bert., Metzeltin &amp; Witkowski
</taxonomicName>
(1996: 253, 254, figs 1: 30–34) (≡ 
<taxonomicName authority="Cholnoky 1959: 51" authorityName="Cholnoky" authorityPageNumber="51" authorityYear="1959" box="[151,841,1762,1788]" genus="Navicula" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="variety" species="subcostulata" variety="avittata">
<emphasis box="[151,429,1763,1788]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Navicula subcostulata</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[493,588,1763,1788]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cholnoky, B. J." box="[598,841,1762,1788]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref26412" refString="Cholnoky, B. J. (1959) Neue und seltene Diatomeen aus Afrika. IV. Diatomeen aus der Kaap-Provinz. Osterreichische Botanische Zeitschrift 106: 1 - 69. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 01278995" type="journal article" year="1959">Cholnoky 1959: 51</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, figs 6: 265–269) and a taxon named as “ 
<taxonomicName class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittata">
<emphasis box="[1365,1386,1763,1788]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis box="[151,247,1801,1826]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H. &amp; Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A." box="[305,656,1801,1827]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="247 - 276" refId="ref27546" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H., Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A. (1996) Hippodonta gen. nov. Iconographia Diatomologica 4: 247 - 276." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lange-Bertalot 
<emphasis box="[505,569,1801,1826]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al.</emphasis>
(1996
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 1: 35–40). Nevertheless, the latter two taxa do not have protracted valve ends and have more rhombic valve outlines. Furthermore, the central area of both 
<taxonomicName box="[1310,1435,1840,1866]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittata">
<emphasis box="[1310,1331,1840,1865]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1346,1435,1840,1865]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="sensu Lange-Bertalot et al. (1996)" authorityName="Lange-Bertalot" authorityYear="1996" box="[201,775,1878,1904]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittata">
<emphasis box="[201,222,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis box="[275,364,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittata</emphasis>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H. &amp; Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A." box="[445,775,1878,1904]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="247 - 276" refId="ref27546" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H., Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A. (1996) Hippodonta gen. nov. Iconographia Diatomologica 4: 247 - 276." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lange-Bertalot 
<emphasis box="[630,689,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al.</emphasis>
(1996)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is never expanded to the valve margins at the middle of the valve and is quite small and not clearly defined. The central area of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[1045,1249,1917,1943]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittatiformis">
<emphasis box="[1045,1066,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1083,1249,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">avittatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is transversely elongated into a panduriform to unilateral fascia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1105,2020]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1435,152,216]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[198,508,1995,2020]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="avittatiformis">
<emphasis box="[198,508,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Hippodonta avittatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pavlov &amp; Levkov &amp; Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[741,897,1994,2020]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="angustata">
<emphasis box="[741,762,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[782,897,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">angustata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(this study, 
<figureCitation box="[1055,1223,1994,2020]" captionStart="FIGURES 308–364" captionStartId="47.[151,269,1730,1754]" captionTargetBox="[289,1301,194,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-72@47.[264,1323,194,1706]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 308–364: LM micrographs. Figs 308–328. Hippodonta avittatiformis (type material). Figs 327, 328. Images of complete frustules in girdle view. Figs 329–342. Hippodonta angustata (type material). Figs 343–349. Hippodonta cocquytiae (type material). Figs 350–353. Hippodonta conspicua (type material). Figs 354–364. Hippodonta minuta (type material). Fig. 354. Complete frustule in girdle view. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5072000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5072000/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs 329–342</figureCitation>
) in regard to the appearance, pattern and density of the striae. Still, the valve ends of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pavlov &amp; Levkov &amp; Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[998,1157,152,178]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="angustata">
<emphasis box="[998,1019,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1037,1157,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">angustata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not protracted and broadly cuneate, and the central area is consistently a well-defined fascia.
</paragraph>
